<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the SINGLE `sys_ws_definition`
    row that declares the Case Submit Scripted REST API namespace inside the
    scoped application `x_[scope]`. This is the API "container" record - the
    namespace, base URL, and authentication policy that hosts the actual POST
    operation handler at the paired sibling
    `./sys_ws_operation_x_[scope]_case_submit_post.xml`.

    PURPOSE (AAP Section 0.4.3 / Section 0.4.4 / Section 0.5.1):

      AAP Section 0.4.3 (Design Pattern): "Anonymous portal via scripted REST
      + Experience widget - Two scripted REST endpoints execute at platform-
      default elevated privilege, but their request/response shapes whitelist
      exactly the fields specified by the user, giving anonymous callers no
      path to internal data."

      AAP Section 0.4.4 (UI Design - External Experience Portal UI):
      "Page 1 - Case Submission: a simple form with five inputs (subject,
      type, description, requester_name, requester_email). On submit, calls
      the scripted REST endpoint, displays a confirmation panel showing the
      returned case number and a friendly 'Your case has been submitted'
      message."

      AAP Section 0.5.1 (in-scope artifact verbatim):
      "servicenow-case-management-poc/portal/rest/sys_ws_definition_x_[scope]_case_submit.xml -
      Scripted REST endpoint: POST anonymously allowed; creates x_[scope]_case
      in Draft; returns {number}. Whitelisted fields only."

      This is the foundational artifact that, together with the paired
      sys_ws_operation record, registers the URL `/api/x_[scope]/case_submit`
      with the ServiceNow REST router. Without this record, the operation
      record would have no parent definition and the platform would not route
      requests to the endpoint at all (HTTP 404 from the routing layer).

    DEFINITION-VS-OPERATION RECORD SEPARATION (ServiceNow data-model):

      ServiceNow's Scripted REST API data-model splits a single REST endpoint
      across two records:

        1. sys_ws_definition (THIS file) - the API "container":
             - Defines `name`, `api_id`, `namespace`, `active` flag, and
               authentication policy (`requires_authentication`,
               `requires_acl_authorization`, `requires_snc_internal_role`,
               `enforce_acl`).
             - Contains NO handler scripts.
             - One definition can host multiple operations (e.g., a single
               API with both POST and GET on different paths). For our case,
               each definition has exactly ONE operation, but the separation
               is still required by the platform's data model.

        2. sys_ws_operation (SIBLING file
             ./sys_ws_operation_x_[scope]_case_submit_post.xml) - the
             actual HTTP-method handler:
             - References this definition via `<web_service_definition>` field
               (resolved by `sys_update_name` lookup against THIS record's
               `<sys_update_name>`).
             - Defines `http_method` (POST), `relative_path` (empty / root for
               this single-operation API), `consumes`/`produces`
               (application/json), and the `operation_script` body that
               actually handles incoming HTTP requests.
             - The operation's script delegates field whitelisting and
               persistence to `../../script_includes/x_[scope]_CasePortalService.xml`
               via `new x_[scope].CasePortalService().submitCase(payload)`.

      This separation matches ArkCase's Spring-bean architecture:

        - `acm-services/acm-service-portal-gateway/src/main/java/com/armedia/
          acm/portalgateway/service/DefaultPluggablePortalRequestService.java`
          line 48 ("public class DefaultPluggablePortalRequestService
          implements PortalRequestService") is the Spring-bean container -
          the analog of THIS sys_ws_definition record (the namespace + URL
          prefix).
        - `DefaultPluggablePortalRequestService.submitRequest(String portalId,
          String portalUserId, PortalRequest request)` (line 60-65) is the
          actual handler method - the analog of the paired sys_ws_operation
          record.

      The same separation-of-concerns principle is preserved: the "container"
      knows the URL/auth policy; the "handler" knows the actual request
      processing. No Java code is byte-for-byte ported (the Java code is
      consulted ONLY for semantic reference per AAP Section 0.5.1 and
      Section 0.8.1).

    URL PATH COMPOSITION:

      The full URL is composed by the platform from `<namespace>` + `<api_id>`:

          /api/<namespace>/<api_id>
          /api/x_[scope]/case_submit

      Note specifically:

        - `<namespace>` = `x_[scope]` (the scope identifier prefix). The PDI
          auto-resolves `x_[scope]` to the actual scope id at App Engine
          Studio creation time.
        - `<api_id>` = `case_submit` (BARE, without the scope prefix). The
          platform automatically prefixes the URL with `<namespace>`. Putting
          the scope prefix in `<api_id>` would result in a doubled prefix
          (`/api/x_[scope]/x_[scope]_case_submit`), which is incorrect.
        - This matches AAP Section 0.5.1 verbatim ("api_id = case_submit") and
          the convention documented in the AAP's "design pattern" entry for
          Anonymous portal via scripted REST.

      The `<sys_update_name>sys_ws_definition_x_[scope]_case_submit</sys_update_name>`
      cross-record identifier IS scope-prefixed, because `sys_update_name` is
      a global identifier across all scoped apps on the PDI. The operation
      record's `<web_service_definition>` reference resolves against this
      `sys_update_name`, NOT against `<api_id>`.

    UNAUTHENTICATED ANONYMOUS-ACCESS DESIGN (AAP Section 0.4.4 verbatim:
    "two unauthenticated pages"):

      Four configuration flags work together to make this a true public
      anonymous endpoint at the API-definition level:

        1. <requires_authentication>false</requires_authentication>
           Anonymous access ALLOWED at the definition level. CRITICAL.
           Even if the operation record permits anonymous access, the
           definition's setting is checked first. If THIS were `true`,
           the platform would reject anonymous requests before evaluating
           the operation's settings.

        2. <requires_acl_authorization>false</requires_acl_authorization>
           No ACL check at definition level. The field whitelist enforced
           by the Script Include `x_[scope].CasePortalService` is the
           security perimeter, not table-level ACLs.

        3. <requires_snc_internal_role>false</requires_snc_internal_role>
           No SNC-internal-role requirement.

        4. <enforce_acl/>
           Empty (no ACL roster enforced at this layer).

      All four flags must be set; omitting any one OR changing the polarity
      breaks the anonymous-access guarantee, breaks Validation Gate 4
      ("Portal - submission"), and breaks the AAP's "two unauthenticated
      pages" requirement.

      The agent prompt's Phase 8 (Critical Authoring Rule 1) explicitly
      mandates each of these four values. The operation record (sibling
      file ./sys_ws_operation_x_[scope]_case_submit_post.xml) ALSO sets
      requires_authentication=false for layered consistency - both records
      must permit anonymous, otherwise the request fails.

    CONSUMES / PRODUCES (cascading defaults):

      <consumes/> and <produces/> are intentionally EMPTY at the definition
      level. The operation record specifies `application/json` for both.
      The definition's empty values mean "use whatever the operation
      specifies" - the platform's standard cascading-defaults pattern. Any
      caller posting `application/json` to /api/x_[scope]/case_submit will
      be matched by the operation's content-type filter; any caller
      requesting a non-JSON content type will receive HTTP 406 from the
      operation layer (not from THIS definition record).

      <consumes_customized>false</consumes_customized> and
      <produces_customized>false</produces_customized> tell the platform
      to use the platform-default content-type negotiation rather than a
      custom override. Setting them to `true` would require additional
      <consumes>/<produces> values to be authored on THIS record, which
      would conflict with the operation's content-type declarations.

    ACTIVE FLAG (AAP Section 0.7.1 verbatim - "Confirm post-commit
    deployable state"):

      <active>true</active> is REQUIRED so the platform routes requests to
      the endpoint. An inactive (`<active>false</active>`) definition would
      result in HTTP 404 from the platform's request-routing layer, before
      the operation script runs. This satisfies AAP Section 0.7.1's
      post-commit verification requirement that the Experience Portal be
      "accessible at [instance URL]/x_[scope]_portal" and that submitting
      a case from the portal results in a successful HTTP 200 response.

    SCOPE BINDING (AAP Sections 0.5.2 and 0.7.2):

      <sys_scope> and <sys_package> reference the scoped application by its
      actual scope NAME (`x_[scope]`), not by sys_id. This matches the
      sibling-file convention used by every other XML record in this scoped
      application:

        - ../../app/sys_scope/x_[scope].xml carries `<name>x_[scope]</name>`
          and `<source>x_[scope]</source>`.
        - ../../app/sys_app/x_[scope]_case_management.xml carries
          `<scope>x_[scope]</scope>` and `<vendor_prefix>x_[scope]</vendor_prefix>`.
        - All sibling dictionary entries (../../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_*.xml),
          choices, tables, roles, ACLs, and the parent portal record
          (../sp_portal_x_[scope]_case_portal.xml) use
          `<sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_[scope]</sys_scope>`
          and `<sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_[scope]">x_[scope]</sys_package>`.

      Update Set re-import resolves cross-references by matching the
      <sys_scope> text-node value against the scope record's <name>/<source>
      fields. Using `x_[scope]_case_management` (rather than `x_[scope]`)
      would fail to match and trigger a preview error on fresh-PDI re-import,
      breaking AAP Section 0.7.3 Validation Gate 7 ("Update Set integrity").
      Therefore THIS record uses `x_[scope]` consistently with every sibling.

      The `display_value="Case Management"` and `source="x_[scope]"` attributes
      are descriptive metadata that ServiceNow uses for human-readable display
      on the Update Set preview page; the actual reference resolution uses
      the text-node values.

    NO HARDCODED SYS_IDS (AAP Section 0.7.2):

      The ONLY sys_id literal in this file is `<sys_id>` itself (THIS
      record's own primary key). Per AAP Section 0.7.2, the no-hardcoded-
      sys_id rule applies to references TO OTHER records, not to a record's
      own identity primary key. The record's <sys_id> is the deterministic
      32-char lowercase hex MD5 of the canonical sys_update_name:

          printf '%s' 'sys_ws_definition_x_[scope]_case_submit' | md5sum | cut -c1-32
          -> ef9090a5b03f1a36c248ce65065a1b74

      The MD5 derivation guarantees that re-generation of this Update Set on
      any agent run produces a byte-identical <sys_id> (no random UUIDs),
      which is required for clean Update-Set re-import on a fresh PDI without
      creating duplicate sys_ws_definition rows. All cross-references
      (<sys_scope>, <sys_package>) resolve by NAME against stable identifiers.

    NO PII, NO EMAIL (AAP Section 0.7.2):

      The description below contains ZERO PII (no real names, no real email
      addresses, no real organization names, no real case content). Email
      notifications are explicitly disabled on the PDI per AAP Section 0.7.2
      ("Email-disabled constraint"). This sys_ws_definition record contains
      NO scripts and therefore NO `gs.eventQueue(...)` calls; the constraint
      is reaffirmed here for context with the paired operation record.

    [scope] PLACEHOLDER PRESERVATION (AAP Section 0.7.2):

      All `x_[scope]_*` references preserve the literal `[scope]` placeholder
      in square brackets - in <api_id>'s embedded scope context (NOT used here
      since api_id is bare), in <namespace>, in <sys_update_name>, in
      <sys_scope>, and in <sys_package>. The PDI auto-resolves [scope] to the
      actual scope id (e.g., `12345` becomes `x_12345`) at App Engine Studio
      creation time when the Update Set is imported. This placeholder
      convention is observed consistently across every sibling XML in this
      scoped application; substituting an actual scope id here would diverge
      from the sibling convention and break re-import portability across
      different PDIs.

    XML CONVENTIONS HONORED (matching every sibling file in this app):

      - First line: <?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
      - Wrapper element: <record_update table="sys_ws_definition"> matching
        the agent prompt's Phase 1 specification and the sibling pattern used
        by ../sp_portal_x_[scope]_case_portal.xml,
        ../../tables/x_[scope]_case.xml, and other primary-record XMLs.
      - Inner element: <sys_ws_definition action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">.
      - Indentation: 4 spaces for record fields (matching sibling convention).
      - Element ordering: alphabetical within the record (matching sibling
        convention; e.g., `active` before `api_id` before `consumes` before
        `description`...).
      - sys_scope text-node value: `x_[scope]` (NOT `x_[scope]_case_management`),
        matching every sibling XML in this scoped app per the actual scope
        record's <name>x_[scope]</name>.
      - sys_package text-node value: `x_[scope]` with `source="x_[scope]"`
        attribute, matching the sys_app record's <scope>x_[scope]</scope>
        per ../../app/sys_app/x_[scope]_case_management.xml.
      - Deterministic 32-char lowercase hex sys_id:
        MD5("sys_ws_definition_x_[scope]_case_submit") =
        ef9090a5b03f1a36c248ce65065a1b74. Re-generation of this XML is
        byte-identical (no random UUIDs).
      - Audit fields: <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by> and
        <sys_created_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_created_on> for stable
        repeatable timestamps (the same date is used by EVERY sibling
        record in this scoped app for repeatable XML re-generation).
      - No smart quotes, no leading/trailing whitespace, no BOM. Strict XML
        conformance for ServiceNow Update Set re-import preview (AAP
        Section 0.7.3 validation gate 7 - Update Set integrity).

    SOURCE-SIDE SEMANTIC REFERENCE (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported per
    AAP Section 0.5.1):

      acm-services/acm-service-portal-gateway/src/main/java/com/armedia/
      acm/portalgateway/service/DefaultPluggablePortalRequestService.java
        line 48 - "public class DefaultPluggablePortalRequestService
                   implements PortalRequestService"
        line 60-65 - public PortalResponse submitRequest(String portalId,
                     String portalUserId, PortalRequest request) throws
                     PortalRequestServiceException { ... return
                     getServiceProvider(request.getRequestType())
                     .submitRequest(portalId, portalUserId, request); }

      ArkCase implements anonymous portal submission via a Java Spring
      service (DefaultPluggablePortalRequestService) that resolves a
      PortalRequestServiceProvider bean by request type and forwards the
      submitRequest(...) call. The ServiceNow target eliminates the Spring
      bean indirection entirely - this sys_ws_definition record IS the
      "container" (analog of the Spring bean configuration: namespace +
      URL prefix + auth policy), and the paired sys_ws_operation record IS
      the "handler" (analog of the submitRequest method body). The
      submission widget's client-side script invokes
      POST /api/x_[scope]/case_submit and the platform routes to the
      operation's script, which delegates to
      `new x_[scope].CasePortalService().submitCase(payload)` - the
      ServiceNow analog of ArkCase's getServiceProvider(...).submitRequest(...)
      provider-resolution-and-forward pattern.

      The Java reference is consulted ONLY for semantic shape (the public
      API of submitRequest's portalId / portalUserId / PortalRequest /
      PortalResponse); no Java code is ported.

    CROSS-REFERENCES (AAP Section 0.5.2 dependency ordering):

      THIS RECORD MUST LOAD AFTER:
        - ../../app/sys_scope/x_[scope].xml (scope record; <sys_scope>
          cross-reference resolves against this record's <name>x_[scope]</name>)
        - ../../app/sys_app/x_[scope]_case_management.xml (scoped application
          record; <sys_package> cross-reference resolves against this
          record's <scope>x_[scope]</scope>)

      THIS RECORD SHOULD LOAD BEFORE (but ServiceNow's two-pass import
      tolerates any order within the same Update Set, since references
      resolve by name):
        - ./sys_ws_operation_x_[scope]_case_submit_post.xml (the POST
          operation record; <web_service_definition> cross-reference resolves
          against this record's <sys_update_name>)
        - ../widgets/sp_widget_x_[scope]_case_submission_widget.xml (the
          widget calls POST /api/x_[scope]/case_submit, transitively
          dependent on this URL being registered with the platform's REST
          router)

      THIS RECORD HAS NO ANCESTOR DEPENDENCY OUTSIDE THE SCOPED APPLICATION
      (per AAP Section 0.7.2 scope-namespace exclusivity - zero global
      writes; the sys_ws_definition table itself is OOB but it accepts
      records from any scope).

    VALIDATION-GATE MAPPING (AAP Section 0.7.3 - the seven validation
    gates):

      This record is the FOUNDATIONAL artifact for Validation Gate 4:

        Gate 4 ("Portal - submission"): "Case created from unauthenticated
          portal submission - Case appears in internal list with Draft
          status and correct case number." The four anonymous-access flags
          (requires_authentication=false, requires_acl_authorization=false,
          requires_snc_internal_role=false, enforce_acl empty) at the
          definition level enable anonymous access to the API namespace.
          The <api_id>case_submit</api_id> and <namespace>x_[scope]</namespace>
          together determine the URL path /api/x_[scope]/case_submit that
          the submission widget targets via fetch()/$http.post(). Without
          this definition record, the operation record would have no parent
          definition and the platform would not register the endpoint at
          all - anonymous callers would receive HTTP 404 from the routing
          layer.

      Gates 1 (data model), 2 (workflow), 3 (ACLs), 5 (portal-lookup),
      6 (dashboards), and 7 (Update Set integrity) are not directly
      affected by this file (Gate 5 is governed by the parallel
      sys_ws_definition_x_[scope]_case_status_lookup.xml record; Gate 7
      requires this file to be well-formed XML, which it is).

      This file is one of two foundational artifacts (this + the operation
      record at ./sys_ws_operation_x_[scope]_case_submit_post.xml) that
      together implement the submission endpoint. Both must be present and
      both must permit anonymous access for Gate 4 to pass.
-->
<record_update table="sys_ws_definition">
    <sys_ws_definition action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <active>true</active>
        <api_id>case_submit</api_id>
        <consumes/>
        <consumes_customized>false</consumes_customized>
        <description>Scripted REST API definition for the Case Submit endpoint. Provides anonymously-accessible POST /api/x_[scope]/case_submit for the unauthenticated Experience Portal submission widget. The actual HTTP-method handler lives in the paired sys_ws_operation record (sys_ws_operation_x_[scope]_case_submit_post.xml). The handler delegates field whitelisting and persistence to the x_[scope].CasePortalService Script Include. Replaces ArkCase's acm-service-portal-gateway anonymous-submission pattern (DefaultPluggablePortalRequestService.submitRequest). Per AAP Sections 0.4.3, 0.4.4, 0.5.1.</description>
        <enforce_acl/>
        <name>Case Submit</name>
        <namespace>x_[scope]</namespace>
        <produces/>
        <produces_customized>false</produces_customized>
        <requires_acl_authorization>false</requires_acl_authorization>
        <requires_authentication>false</requires_authentication>
        <requires_snc_internal_role>false</requires_snc_internal_role>
        <sys_class_name>sys_ws_definition</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_created_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_created_on>
        <sys_id>ef9090a5b03f1a36c248ce65065a1b74</sys_id>
        <sys_mod_count>0</sys_mod_count>
        <sys_name>Case Submit</sys_name>
        <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_[scope]">x_[scope]</sys_package>
        <sys_policy/>
        <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_[scope]</sys_scope>
        <sys_update_name>sys_ws_definition_x_[scope]_case_submit</sys_update_name>
        <sys_updated_by>admin</sys_updated_by>
        <sys_updated_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_updated_on>
    </sys_ws_definition>
</record_update>
